ASSEMBLY OF COMPONENTS
1. Best building practices (link to detailed resources for assembly process)
a. ESD safety
b. POST components outside case to check for issues
c. Careful handling of components (such as CPU)
TROUBLESHOOTING
2. Common Issues
a. Nothing happens
i. 24 pin ATX
ii. CPU Power
iii. PSU plugged in (and turned on)
iv. BIOS issue (need to update to support newer CPU in older MOBO etc)
v. Front panel headers
b. No display, or not displaying in correct resolution
i. GPU is properly seated
ii. Monitor is plugged into the right input (GPU, not MOBO)
iii. No GPU power
c. System instability
i. Overheating (CPU fan power)
ii. No thermal paste
iii. Bad RAM (try one stick at a time)
d. Storage device not showing up
i. For SATA drives, check data AND power connections at device and
MOBO.
ii. For M.2/PCIe devices, make sure drive is inserted into the slot correctly
COMMON TROUBLESHOOTING STEPS
(Troubleshooting)
1. Nothing Happens
a. PSU on and plugged in?
b. 24 pin ATX connected?
c. CPU seated correctly?
d. CPU power connected?
e. Correct BIOS (newer CPU in older motherboard)
2. No Display Output
a. Correct monitor input?
b. Plugged into the GPU and not the motherboard?
c. Does the GPU have power and is seated in the PCIe slot correctly?
3. System Instability (crashes)
a. Proper cooling? (CPU fan connected, thermal paste on heatsink)
b. RAM issue? (try one stick at a time, could be bad RAM)
4. Storage/Boot device not showing up
a. Check SATA data and power (if applicable)
b. Check M.2/PCIe slot (if applicable)
BEST PRACTICES IN WHEN ASSEMBLING
1. ESD Safety
a. Ensure connection to ground
b. ESD Strap, or plug in PSU to wall (keep it turned OFF) and occasionally touch
metal casing to ensure you stay grounded.
2. Handle components carefully
a. Do not touch bare PCBs with hands
3. Be gentle when inserting components and check connections
a. Do not force components, they should not require a lot of force.
b. Check to see if connections are keyed (only go in one way) and are inserted
FULLY.

Glossary:
1. GPU (Graphics Processing Unit): Responsible for rendering high-quality graphics and
performing complex computations. This is important for the visual fidelity and
performance of the PC required for AAA games. Also referred to as a graphics card or
video card.
2. CPU (Central Processing Unit): Responsible for performing the vast majority of
processing tasks. Performance depends on the clock speed, usually measured in GHz
(gigahertz), and the number of cores. Also referred to as a processor.
3. Storage: Responsible for storing all of your files, programs, and other data on your
computer. The types of storage vary by physical size, type of storage device, and the
amount of physical memory on the device. There are two main types of storage that you
can put in your PC
a. Hard Disk Drive (HDD): The HDD is a storage device that is mostly used to store
most of your big folders, such as games, videos, pictures, and files. Large
amounts of storage on an HDD is very affordable. The HDD is connected to the
motherboard via SATA cables that go into the SATA ports on the motherboard.
b. Solid State Drive SSD: The SSD is a storage device that should be used for
programs that you want to run or boot up quickly, such as your operating system.
i. M.2.: M.2. drives are inserted directly into the M.2. port on the
motherboard. Some motherboards do not have M.2. slots, so be careful
when choosing your motherboard if you want to use a M.2. SSD
ii. 2.5-Inch SATA SSD: These SATA SSDs are similar to HDDs in the sense
that you must plug them into the motherboard with a SATA cable into the
SATA ports.
4. RAM (Random Access Memory): Responsible for the “short term memory” of your PC.
The faster and larger your RAM, the faster your computer will be able to access the data
you want i.e. opening a file, website, or video. Also referred to as memory
5. I/O Ports: I/O stands for Input/Output. This means it is responsible for the computer
interacting with the real world. Common peripherals include a mouse, keyboard,
headphones, webcam, and flash drives. To connect these devices, you must plug them
into their designated I/O port on the motherboard.
